{
  "texts": [
    "A common approach is to use the (normalized) generation likelihood (or the reciprocal of perplexity (Chen et al., 1998)) as an uncertainty measure.",
    "However, many popular LLMs, such as ChatGPT and GPT-4, do not provide access to token probabilities in their APIs, rendering this approach inapplicable.",
    "Additionally, sampling-based methods (Wang et al., 2022; Si et al., 2022; Kuhn et al., 2023) examine the deviation among multiple outputs generated from the original input.",
    "However, when an LLM makes a confidently incorrect prediction, resampling tends to yield similar results, leading to an overconfident and poorly calibrated score.",
    "Epistemic uncertainty, on the other hand, is due to the lack of knowledge or suboptimal modeling."
  ]
}